Attribute Information:¶

(1) age: age of primary beneficiary.

(2) sex: insurance contractor gender, female, male.

(3) bmi: Body mass index, providing an understanding of body, weights that are relatively high or low relative to height, objective index of body weight (kg / m ^ 2) using the ratio of height to weight, ideally 18.5 to 24.9.

(4) children: Number of children covered by health insurance / Number of dependents.

(5) smoker: Smoking

(6) region: the beneficiary's residential area in the US, northeast, southeast, southwest, northwest.

(7) charges: Individual medical costs billed by health insurance.

Add a column to the dataframe to categorise an individual as underweight,Normal weight, Over weight or Obese.¶

Reference : https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/educational/lose_wt/BMI/bmicalc.htm¶

BMI Categories:¶

Underweight = <18.5¶

Normal weight = 18.5–24.9¶

Overweight = 25–29.9¶

Obesity = BMI of 30 or greater¶

In [11]:
df['weight_type'] = df['bmi'].apply(lambda x: 'underweight' 
                if x <= 18.5 
                else ('normalweight' if (18.5 <= x <= 24.9)
                      else ('overweight' if(25 <= x <= 29.9) 
                            else 'obese')))

(4) Hypothesis testing¶

(4.1) Do charges of people who smoke differ significantly from the people who don't?¶

In [26]:
ax1 = sns.scatterplot(df['age'],df['charges'],hue=df['smoker'],palette=["red","green"],alpha=0.7);
ax1.set_title("Age vs Charges",fontsize=20);
ax1.set_xlabel("Age",fontsize=15);
ax1.set_ylabel("Charges",fontsize=15);
plt.setp(ax1.get_legend().get_texts(), fontsize='15');
plt.setp(ax1.get_xticklabels(), fontsize=15);
plt.setp(ax1.get_yticklabels(), fontsize=15);

Visual representation shows that smokers pay more than non-smokers for the same age.¶

To prove with the statistical evidence,¶

(*) Null Hypothesis or H0 : There is no difference between smoker and non-smoker for the medical charges.¶

(*) Alternate Hypothesis or Ha : Charges are not the same.¶

(*) $\alpha$ or level of significance = 5% or 0.05¶

In [27]:
len(df[df["smoker"]=="yes"]["charges"]) , len(df[df["smoker"]=="no"]["charges"])
Out[27]:
(274, 1064)

Since the sample size is well above 30 we will use "Two-Sample Z Test" to check if the sample mean are same or not at a significance level of 0.05¶

In [28]:
p_alpha = 0.05
h0 = "there is no difference between smoker and non-smoker for the medical charges."
h1 = "there is a difference between smoker and non-smoker for the medical charges"
In [29]:
# Method-1 using Z Test
z_stat,z_p_value= ztest(df[df["smoker"]=="yes"]["charges"], df[df["smoker"]=="no"]["charges"])
print(z_stat,z_p_value)

if z_p_value < p_alpha :
    print(f"Reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value {z_p_value:.4} is less than {p_alpha:.4}.\nHence,{h1}")
else:
    print(f"Failing to reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value {z_p_value:.4} is greater than {p_alpha:.4}.\nHence,{h0} ")
    
    

46.664921172723716 0.0
Reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value 0.0 is less than 0.05.
Hence,there is a difference between smoker and non-smoker for the medical charges
In [30]:
# Method 2 using T-Test of independent variable
t_stat,t_p_value= stats.ttest_ind(df[df["smoker"]=="yes"]["charges"], df[df["smoker"]=="no"]["charges"],axis=0 )
print(t_stat,t_p_value)

if t_p_value < p_alpha :
    print(f"Reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value {t_p_value:.4} is less than {p_alpha:.4}.\nHence,{h1}")
else:
    print(f"Failing to reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value {t_p_value:.4} is greater than {p_alpha:.4}.\nHence,{h0} ")
    

46.664921172723716 8.271435842177219e-283
Reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value 8.271e-283 is less than 0.05.
Hence,there is a difference between smoker and non-smoker for the medical charges

Hence it can be confirmed through a statistical evidence that charges vary significantly between smokers and non-smokers.¶

Both t and z test confirms the alternate hypothesis.¶

To prove with the statistical evidence,¶

(*) Null Hypothesis or H0 : Gender has no effect on the BMI i.e BMI of male and female are same.¶

(*) Alternate Hypothesis or Ha : Gender has an effect on the BMI i.e BMI of male and female are different.¶

(*) 𝛼 or level of significance = 5% or 0.05¶

(4.3) Is the proportion of smokers significantly different in different genders?¶

In [36]:
ax1 = sns.countplot(df['smoker'],hue=df['sex'],palette=["red","blue"],alpha=0.7);

Visual comparison shows that the gender has an effect on the smoking habits.¶

To prove with the statistical evidence,¶

(*) Null Hypothesis or H0 : Gender has no effect on the smoking habits.¶

(*) Alternate Hypothesis or Ha : Gender has an effect on the smoking habits.¶

(*) 𝛼 or level of significance = 5% or 0.05¶

(*) We will use Chi-Square test the statistical significance as these are catogorical variables.¶

(*) We will use chi2_contingency API as we are testing the relationship between the categorical variables "smoker" and "sex".¶

In [37]:
# Creating the contingency table 
cont_table = pd.crosstab(df['sex'],df['smoker'])
cont_table
Out[37]:
smoker no yes
sex
female 547 115
male 517 159
In [38]:
p_alpha = 0.05
h0 = "there is no effect of gender on the smoking habits."
h1 = "there is an effect of gender on the smoking habits."
In [39]:
chi2_stats, chi2_p, dof, expect = stats.chi2_contingency(cont_table)

# chi2_stats, chi2_p, dof, _

print(f"(1) Chi2 Statistic : {chi2_stats:.4}\n(2) p_value : {chi2_p:.4}\n(3) Degree of Freedom : {dof}")

if chi2_p < p_alpha :
    print(f"\nReject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value {chi2_p:.4} is less than {p_alpha:.4}.\nHence,{h1}")
else:
    print(f"\nFailing to reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value {chi2_P:.4} is greater than {p_alpha:.4}.\nHence,{h0} ")
    

(1) Chi2 Statistic : 7.393
(2) p_value : 0.006548
(3) Degree of Freedom : 1

Reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value 0.006548 is less than 0.05.
Hence,there is an effect of gender on the smoking habits.

plt.setp(ax1.get_yticklabels(), fontsize=15);

There does not seem to be apparent effect of number of children on the BMI.¶

To prove with the statistical evidence,¶

(*) Null Hypothesis or H0 : The number of children has no effect on the BMI of women i.e means across sample are not different.¶

(*) Alternate Hypothesis or Ha : The number of children has an effect on the BMI of women. i.e means across samples are different.¶

(*) 𝛼 or level of significance = 5% or 0.05¶

(*) We will use ANOVA test to determine if the sample mean is same across all groups or different i.e BMI is same across groups of women with 0,1 and 2 children. Before we use ANOVA we need to test for normality and variance criteria.¶

h1 = "the number of children has an effect on the BMI of women. i.e means across samples are different."
In [45]:
#  Method 1: Testing with F statistic 
f_stat,f_p_value = stats.f_oneway(no_child,one_child,two_child,axis=0)

f_stat,f_p_value

print(f"(1) F Statistic : {f_stat:.4}\n(2) p_value : {f_p_value:.4}")

if f_p_value < p_alpha :
    print(f"\nReject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value {f_p_value:.4} is less than {p_alpha:.4}.\nHence,{h1}")
else:
    print(f"\nFailing to reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value {f_p_value:.4} is greater than {p_alpha:.4}.\nHence,{h0} ")
    

(1) F Statistic : 0.3345
(2) p_value : 0.7159

Failing to reject the Null Hypothesis H0 as p_value 0.7159 is greater than 0.05.
Hence,the number of children has no effect on the BMI of women i.e means across sample are not different.
